<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="478" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1254,1603]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1254,1279]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Slender body, cylindrical and elongated. Ovoid, prominent ocelli. Distal veins of the costal field slightly reticulated. Phallic complex: wider than long, apical sclerite truncate, wavy and with lateral projections. Ectophallus wide, basal plates circular and elongate, internal process as long as it is wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="478" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1254,1603]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1362,1387]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Etymology.</emphasis>
Alludes to the similar appearance with the species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1085,1212,1362,1387]" class="Insecta" family="Lathiceridae" genus="Neocurtilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1085,1212,1362,1387]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Neocurtilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but more thin and delicate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
